default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHow effective is horizon scanning in Government? Do Ministers and senior officials consider horizon scanning outputs appropriately?
default&#xa0;
default4.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe effectiveness o
defaultf futures research in Government is variable, and is conditioned by a range of factors, some of which are internal to 
defaultD
defaultepartments, some of which are driven by external imperatives and pressures.
default Below, we identify some key factors that
default, in our experience,
default condition whether futures research is effective or not.
default&#xa0;default4.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOne key factor is the need for 
defaultconsiderable resource input from, and engagement by, domain experts
default 
default(e.g. 
defaultscientific specialists in the subject in question
default)
default, and policy- and decision-makers in Govern
defaultment. 
defaultWhilst successful research generally requires a measure of user engagement
default, 
defaulteffective 
defaultfutures research requires continuous involvement of those wishing to use the outputs of the research from procurement to delivery. 
defaultIn short, t
defaulto benefit from 
defaultfutures
default 
defaultresearch
default 
defaultrequires
default 
defaultan investment of 
defaultsustained effort from all those involved, things that are often in short supply in today’s Government. Lack of time 
defaultunderstandably 
defaultoften leads officials
default and 
defaultMinisters
default 
defaultto have to 
defaultconcentrate on delivery of the current age
defaultnda with little time to focus on the future. 
default&#xa0;default4.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe effectiveness of futures research is dependent on those commissioning the research understand
defaulting
default what it can, but 
defaultequally
default importantly, what it cannot provide. For example, there is a tendency to want prediction
default. Futures
default research cannot provide 
defaultthis because the future is generally not predictable
default,
default so 
defaultthe research is
default a tool 
defaultto
default enable policy
default-
defaultmakers
default and politicians 
defaultto reflect on
default how their recommendations and decisions might unfold in a number of possible futures rather than rely on a single explicit or implicit route to the future. This is important, for example, in infrastructure planning and implementation given the timescales 
defaultinvolved which can span decades
default: the imperatives of today, may - or may not - be relevant at the point at which the infrastructure development is completed, so thinking in structured terms about what that future might look like should be helpful
default.
default&#xa0;
default4.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultTherefor
defaulte, to be truly effective, futures research should be used as a tool to enable policy
default-
defaultmakers to test assumptions against a range of possible futures, and to provide orientation around how policy development and decision
default-
defaultmaking may work – or may need to work
default – in the future. The outputs will not be a reflection of the status quo: some methods are specifically designed to shift recipients from their current world view and to enable them to think about what is possible and plausible, not just what is probable. 
defaultIt can therefore create discomfort because it challenges the current world view.
default&#xa0;
