default5.1
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe be
defaultlieve that the Day recommendations are generally well founded, but that some further nuances and steps would help to deliver the recommendations.
default&#xa0;
default5.2
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFutures research uses recognised social science and organisational management participatory 
defaultmethods (expert e
defaultlicitation interviews, questionnaires and workshop techniques)
default, coupled with secondary research including desk-based analysis of relevant research and datasets,
default to identify all aspects of whichever issue being investigated. These include using domain exper
defaultts to identify and understand the interactions between the political, economic, social, technological, legislative and environmental drivers of change (PESTLE analysis), to gain an understanding of whole systems, rather than projections of individual drive
defaultrs
default of change
default. 
defaultGiven this, i
defaultt
default 
defaultmay 
defaultbe best placed under the management of 
defaultthe 
defaultGovernment social science profession whose members have a better understanding of the utility of the outputs of research using social science techniques.
default&#xa0;
default5.3
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCurrently
default, many futures 
defaultresearch projects
default and programmes
default are managed by and report to, central departmental evidence and strategy teams. The research programmes of these teams 
defaultcan be 
defaultdominated by economic research and managed by 
defaultspecialists
default whose training 
defaultrightly 
defaultlends them to gi
defaultve more weight to data
default sourced by more traditional means
default, but who can sometimes find it 
defaultchallenging
default to understand and give credence to the less 
defaultdefined
default outputs gathered using 
defaultfutures research methods
default. Futures research outputs therefore, are
default often perceived
default to be less robust
default, which can lead to a perception that there is less imperative to take action
default. Many 
defaultspecialist
default evidence managers and policy-
defaultmakers are therefore, reluctant to allocate precious time and resources to 
defaultthe 
defaultissues identified by futures resear
defaultch until a greater weight of evidence to sup
defaultport action is available. T
defaulthere is a delicate balance to be 
defaultstruck
default between acting too early and potentially wasting resources or waiting until the weight of evidence is overwhelming
default. However, this has potential to 
defaultleav
defaulte
default action too late
default: at best, this may involve additional cost, at worst, it results in the sort of failure that 
defaultthe 
defaultpolicy process seeks to avoid.
default 
default&#xa0;
default5.4
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFutures research has a creative dimension and 
defaultmethods are often describ
defaulted in 
defaultlanguage that isn’t
default necessarily familiar to policy-
defaultmakers. We 
defaultfind
default that 
defaultdescribing outputs 
defaultusing the language of risk 
defaultassessment and 
defaultman
defaultagement
default,
default 
defaultwhich is more familiar to Government senior officials, can greatly assist in embedding understanding
default. Cra
defaultnfield University has pioneered the integration of risk analysis tools to complement the outputs of futures research with more robust analysis of where future risks and opportunities might lie, and where and when to intervene to gain best value for 
defaultthe tax
defaultpayer. 
defaultHowever, 
defaultwhilst this has helped improve use of outputs for those already familiar with risk terminology, 
defaultwe also identify that training for officials needs to include developing familiarity and understanding of the applications and benefits of both 
defaultfutures and risk research in the policy-making community. 
defaultAdditionally
default, the involvement of Departmental risk managers can be key in 
defaultchallenging, supporting and 
defaultembedding the outputs of futures research with 
defaultpolicy-makers, senior officials and politicians. 
default&#xa0;
default5.5
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWhilst the Day Review sets out a new definition for ‘horizon scanning’ 
defaultacross Government 
defaultthis actually appears to be a definition of futures research. As described earlier, horizon scanning is one of a number of futures research techniques. Government’s 
defaultcontinued use of ‘horizon scanning’ as a catch-all term for all futures research techniques is detrimental in facilitating understanding between policy
default advisors, politicians as decision makers, 
defaultand practitioners. This has the potential to lead to misunders
defaulttandings during 
defaultresearch commissioning and 
defaultprocess, which wastes time and resources on both sides
default, and can create frustration
default. Additionally, it does not demonstrate to 
defaultresearchers
default that Government is an intelligent customer of futures research
default, 
defaultcompromising
default best value
default.
default&#xa0;
default5.6
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe Day Review proposes the identification and use of high-level champions for futures research in Government. This 
defaultreflects established wisdom and experience, and 
defaultwe agree that high-level champion
defaults
default for futures research would be instrumental
default in helping to embed futures thinking across Government and in individual Departments
default. This should 
defaultbuild on the work undertaken by Prof Sir David King and the late Prof Sir Howard Dalton, who 
defaultboth 
defaultpioneered the use of futures research methods to support de
defaultcision-making, across Government and in Defra respectively. 
default&#xa0;
default5.7
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFutures research outputs are a tool to test developing policy to ensure 
defaultresilience
default to future requirements. The next step in using this research to test policy and identify future implications
default,
default h
defaultas until recently been undertaken or led by policy experts within Departments. However, the Day Review suggests that policy-makers now have an expectation that futures research practitioners will identify and provide implications for the future. 
defaultWe presume
default that this reflects Cabinet Office guidance and thinking in outsourcing policy. 
defaultThis is challenging
default for futures research
default: futures researchers are only rarely domain or policy experts in the policy areas they help Departments to investigate – more often, th
defaultey bring new dimensions, evidence, insight and act as facilitators to help experts to identify the implications of future developments for themselves. Policy makers and politicians 
default– or their advisors or delegates - 
defaultneed to be equipped to seek and absorb 
defaultt
defaulthis 
defaultexpertise and insight, compute it, and then make informed decisions. 
defaultTherefore, taken at face value, the recommendation
default represents a step change that will demand a shift in the role of researchers, and has accompanying resource shift implications
default. 
